People get triggered about a lot of things these days… In my own experience I’ve learned that being triggered doesn’t mean that people need to stop doing things that trigger me, it actually just means that I need to work on myself more so that I don’t get triggered so easily. For example: I’ve dyed my hair about a million colors over the years and it used to really bother me when family/friends would express their distaste or make comments about it. One time someone said something like “good you finally dyed it blonde again, I didn’t really like black hair on you” and meant it as a compliment. Things like this used to make me feel really angry and uncomfortable and insecure with this idea that my hair color made such an impact on others’ perception of me. I’ve always seen hair as an accessory—not a permanent bodily fixture… changing it to me is so fun! Like changing your hats or shirts or pants or dresses! Different hair colors for different seasons or moods or occasions is such a fun idea! It makes me excited to think of all the fun possibilities different hair colors and styles can do for a look, outfit or costume! So when people made comments like this I used to get hurt or angry… and then I finally realized something… their comments trigger me because I’m still afraid of what others think of me. I’m still afraid of others judging me. How can I overcome this fear? Work on it. Find the things that make me afraid and expose them again and again until they hurt less. Repeat the scenario. Now someone makes a comment about my hair: I smile really big and usually make a joke and realize the less I take myself seriously, the less hurt or triggered I will ever feel about silly little things like this. Also they will laugh and not make it a big deal either if I don’t! If something makes me happy, I’m going to do it. Period. If it makes others uncomfortable, that means they need to work on whatever it is that’s making them uncomfortable. They need to work in their own triggers. It’s that simple. If everyone just healed their own triggers (take care of your side of the fence and I’ll take care of mine), we’d all get along so much better in so many ways 💕✨ #triggers

Heard this lovely piano piece “Alive” by @andreavanzo_composer a few weeks back and couldn’t help but write some lyrics to it (and extra piano for the chorus)! I wrote this about longing for the child that lives inside of us. At one point we all know how to fly—especially when we’re children—but sometimes things happen that make us forget. It might take a lot of work and healing, but one day we will fly again even if only for a moment ❤️‍🩹🦅 Today’s my birthday so wanted to post something meaningful ☺️ #piano #lyrics #songwriting #howtofly #alive

Check out IVEEN’s stunning acoustic version of The Sown. It’s as if the song has transcended into the Celestial realm! (lol sorry I just had to)

I had the pleasure of meeting IVEEN a few years ago and was blown away by her immense talent. Not only is she a gifted singer and songwriter, but she’s also a multi-instrumentalist, live performer, and language teacher. She’s a true Renaissance woman. Through the inspiring talents of artists like IVEEN, we are reminded of the importance of self-care and the healing power of music. This is what IVEEN says about the song:

“When Eric reached out to me about writing lyrics and vocals for “The Sown” he poured out his heart and soul about some very deep emotions and experiences. I could relate heavily with these experiences in my own life and I thought the concepts from Nightlark of sowing seeds was a beautiful metaphor for taking the time we need to heal from past pains. I love using metaphors a lot in my songs so already having a theme like this was perfect to write a full song with. Growing up playing traditional Irish folk music, I’ve always had a love for story telling and whenever someone gives me a topic and theme to write, the stories write themselves within me, I just have to catch them in time in the air as they pass by before they fly away! Eric is an amazing producer and I love that he and his mom make music together, that’s such a rare gift these days and they are super lucky to have each other 💕”

If you’d like to support IVEEN, Celestial Void, Nightlark, or any of our other talented artists, today is Bandcamp Friday – the perfect day to do so! ❤️

“For a long time, I struggled with the desire to control everything in my life, but that only led to anxiety and stress. It wasn’t until I learned to let go and surrender that I found true peace. Surrendering doesn’t mean giving up; instead, it means accepting the things around us and learning to differentiate between what we can control and what we cannot. Through this process, I learned to let go of expectations and to focus on making the best choices possible in my life. The eye of the storm is a symbol of that peace and safety, even when everything around us is in turmoil. By embracing acceptance and letting go of control, we can find the strength and clarity needed to navigate life’s challenges with grace and resilience” -IVEEN @iveenofficial
